## CACHING — REDIS (SQL primary, write-through)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Strategy: SQL is the source of truth. Redis is a write-through cache.
On write: save to SQL → immediately write to Redis → TTL = 30s.
On read: Redis hit → return. Miss → load from SQL → write to Redis → return.
On Redis failure: log warning, fall through to SQL. Never crash.

Cache keys:
  "flagly:flags:{projectId}:{environmentApiKey}" → JSON flag list (TTL 30s)
  "flagly:project:{projectSlug}" → project + environments metadata (TTL 60s)

IFlagCacheService (Flagly.Application/Common/Interfaces/):
  Task<List<FeatureFlagDto>?> GetFlagsAsync(string cacheKey);
  Task SetFlagsAsync(string cacheKey, List<FeatureFlagDto> flags, TimeSpan ttl);
  Task InvalidateAsync(string cacheKey);
  Task InvalidateByProjectIdAsync(Guid projectId);

RedisFlagCacheService (Flagly.Infrastructure/Caching/):
  - IConnectionMultiplexer via DI
  - System.Text.Json serialization
  - InvalidateByProjectIdAsync: SCAN "flagly:flags:{projectId}:*" → delete batch
  - All Redis errors: catch, Serilog.Log.Warning, return null (never throw)

On any flag / targeting / group / company group change:
  1. Save to DB via UnitOfWork.SaveChangesAsync()
  2. InvalidateByProjectIdAsync(projectId)
  3. Write updated flag list to Redis immediately (write-through)
  4. SDK re-fetches on next poll (≤30s)

